japan 's ministry of justice to try out e - mail service to reduce pressure on office life
the japanese ministry of general affairs today started to promote an advanced internet program . it is hoped that by 2010 , 20 percent of the japanese workforce will be able to carry out " electronic communications " work from home and reduce the pressure brought about by office life and the problem of family breakdown .
at present , there are about 4 million japanese , or six percent of the 63.2 million workforce in japan , using science and technology to work outside the office , a ministry official said .
starting from january , the ministry of justice will have six staff members who will not need to enter the office for at least one day , and can work at home , university , or library through high - speed internet services .
the ministry of justice will then look at the situation and expand the scope of this advanced plan until all 2,500 staff members of the ministry of justice can work at home by 2006 .
the official of the general ministry of justice said that the plan , which enables employees to meet through the internet chat room and the electronic video conference , hopes to " increase the efficiency of the job site . "
he said that e - mail would allow more time for workers to get along with their families and help those who are in need of family help .
he said that the scheme would also reduce the traffic congestion rate , including the emission level of vehicles and the over - crowded problem of trams at peak hours .
he said that the goal of this plan is to " increase the percentage of japanese electronics workers to 10 percent by 2005 by encouraging the sharing of electronic communications technology with private enterprises , and further increase to 20 percent by 2010 . "
pentagon launches unprecedented rescue operation for tsunami victims in asia
the pentagon said today that the pentagon has launched its largest rescue operation in its history to help the tsunami victims in asia , including the mobilization of 20 aircraft carriers , including reconnaissance and supply planes , and tens of thousands of people .
a spokesman for the pentagon and the navy 's junior university , heks , said that after the tsunami disaster that killed more than 80,000 people on the 26th , the us military is facing the challenge of simultaneously launching operations in several areas .
" this is one of the largest humanitarian rescue operations in the pentagon 's history , " he told afp .
lieutenant general kang wei , a military action officer in charge of the joint chiefs of staff , said that they are seeking to assess the scale of the disaster and have sent disaster relief teams to thailand , sri lanka and indonesia .
the pentagon said that the pentagon has sent 20 planes to south asia , including six c - 130 transport planes carrying drinking water and food , five kac - 135 air refueling planes , and nine p3 reconnaissance planes .
the pentagon also mobilized the aircraft carrier " lin kenya " and " li cha " and their ships .
kang wei said that the " linkka " battle group and its 12 helicopters and 9,000 personnel have been sent from hong kong to siem reap bay and will eventually be deployed in the sea off sorenia .
the " li cha " , carrying 25 helicopters , 2,100 marines and 1,400 sailors , has left guam and is expected to arrive in the bay of bengal by january 7 next year .
the pentagon has decided to mobilize five more vessels from guam and two vessels capable of producing fresh water from the base in diego garcia in the indian ocean .
the rescue operation will be directed by a thai military base in the gulf of siem reap , he said .
