rich countries fail to fulfill their commitment to reducing poverty : un
a un - appointed expert group said in a new report that it promised to provide financial assistance to the rich countries with a view to reducing the world 's extremely poor population by half by 2015 , and that it has not yet fulfilled its commitments .
the rich countries in the world have promised to participate in the un 's ambitious " millennium development goals " program in order to improve the fate of the world 's poverty and suffering population .
however , at present , more than 1 billion people in the world have a daily living expenses of less than $ 1 - billion , and 2.7 - billion people are living on less than $ 2 - billion a day . un experts say that the time for the rich countries to fulfill their commitments is very short .
" with the correct mobilization of resources and political will , the development and reform of the developed countries can still be achieved , " said brown , director of the un development program .
un experts said that 22 rich countries in the world promised to provide 0.7 percent of their gross domestic product ( gdp ) aid to developing countries , but they are now only 0.25 percent .
un secretary general annan entrusted the development experts headed by former harvard economist shks to compile the progress report on this goal , including eliminating extreme poverty , popularizing primary education , reducing child mortality , and cracking down on aids and other fatal diseases .
the report said : " the practical solution has already existed , the political structure has been established , and the expenditure can be borne for the first time . now there is only a lack of action . "
